{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01ChrrXHeGSPSvuBbpfhkpDG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so the problem is clear now. The nginx server block for `rate.example.com` only has `location /` with `service_name: \"\"` and `proxy_upstream_name: \"upstream-default-backend\"`. Neither `/api` nor `/health` location blocks are being generated.\n\nThis is very strange because the Ingresses look correct and the endpoints are resolved. Let me think about what could cause this...\n\nActually, I think I see the issue. The ingress-nginx controller stores the backend mapping in a Lua-based dynamic backend system. The location blocks in nginx.conf are mostly templates, and the actual routing is done by Lua at runtime. \n\nThe `$proxy_upstream_name` defaults to \"upstream-default-backend\", but Lua should be overriding it at runtime. The real problem is that `service_name` and `service_port` are both empty in that location block—they should be populated. In ingress-nginx v1.14.1, the paths are handled through Lua with a simplified nginx.conf structure, so the catch-all `location /` might be the template, but Lua should be filling in the actual backend details.\n\nI tested this and got a 404, so the Lua routing isn't working either. The confusing part is that nginx-ingress clearly knows about the `rate-health` Ingress (it's setting `$ingress_name` to it), and `kubectl describe` shows the endpoints are resolved to 10.244.0.173:5678, yet the service name isn't being resolved. I need to check the Lua backend configuration to see if the upstreams are actually registered there.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1376,"cache_read_input_tokens":53039,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1376},"output_tokens":21,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"di