{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019ZXBKG9NDJcHX5682GHZT9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I need to understand why the nginx location blocks aren't being generated properly for the new Ingresses. The backend `demo-stable-echo-80` exists and has endpoints, but the nginx config for `rate.example.com` only has `location /` pointing to the default backend.\n\nWait, I think I understand the issue now. In nginx-ingress v1.14.1, when you have multiple Ingresses for the same host, the paths should be merged and individual location blocks should be created. But what's happening here is:\n- `rate-health` Ingress has path `/health` → but creates `location /` in nginx\n- `rate-api` Ingress has path `/api` → not creating any location block at all\n\nLooking at the nginx config more closely, the `location /` block has `$location_path` set to `/` when it should be `/health`, and `$service_name` is empty. This suggests the Ingress configuration isn't being parsed correctly, possibly related to how nginx-ingress handles multiple paths with the `Prefix` type.\n\nI'm wondering if there's a backend conflict — maybe the `stable-echo` service is already claimed by the `canary-stable` Ingress and nginx-ingress is preventing reuse, or there's some deduplication happening. That error message about \"cannot merge alternative backend\" in the controller logs is suspicious and might be the root cause.\n\nBut the real puzzle is why the nginx config is generating a catch-all `location /` for `rate.example.com` instead of separate blocks for `/health` and `/api`. In newer nginx-ingress versions, the routing is actually handled by Lua rather than location blocks — the `location /` acts as a catch-all and Lua does the per-path routing based on the backends configuration.\n\nThe fact that `service_name` is empty in the location block suggests Lua should be handling the actual backend selection, routing requests to `demo-stable-echo-80` for both paths. So if we're getting a 404, I need to check what Lua is actually deciding — maybe I should look at the controller logs to trace the routing decision.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":418,"cache_read_input_tokens":55745,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":418},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"05deaebe-af88-4439-b66c-5774aca7c1be","uuid":"160d1b86-5d81-4b6c-abe3-db0de0e65d46","request_id":"req_011Cc6e27fQcubMr3nhBA3g2"}
